{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "Sarah cuts her finger while cooking. Over the next few hours, she notices the area becomes red and slightly swollen, but no infection develops.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Antibodies take time to produce and require the adaptive immune response. The immediate response comes from different mechanisms.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Antibodies immediately attacked bacteria at the wound site"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Memory cells help with faster responses to previously encountered threats, but they don't explain the immediate defense at a fresh wound.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Memory cells recognized the bacteria from a previous infection"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Cells like macrophages are part of the immediate response system. They patrol tissues and consume foreign material quickly, often preventing infection before the slower, targeted response is needed.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Cells that engulf foreign material destroyed bacteria before they could multiply"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "B cells and antibody production are part of the slower, targeted response. The quick prevention of infection in this case points to the faster-acting defense system.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "B cells produced proteins that stuck to the bacteria"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What likely prevented infection here?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A child recovers from chickenpox at age 5. Twenty years later, she's exposed to the same virus when caring for her sick nephew but doesn't get sick.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Physical barriers don't learn or improve based on past infections. They work the same way against all invaders, whether encountered before or not.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Her skin and mucus barriers were stronger as an adult"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! After the first infection, some immune cells become memory cells that remember the specific virus. When exposed again, they trigger a rapid response that eliminates the threat before symptoms develop.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Cells retained information about the virus and responded quickly"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This doesn't explain why she's protected against this specific virus. The protection is targeted to chickenpox because she had it before.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Adult immune systems are naturally stronger than children's"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The scenario states it's the same virus. Her protection comes from her immune system's ability to remember past threats, not from changes in the virus.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "The virus mutated and couldn't infect her anymore"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Why didn't she get chickenpox again?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A researcher discovers that a particular patient's immune cells produce Y-shaped proteins that bind specifically to a certain bacterial surface protein, but not to other bacteria.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "These proteins don't directly kill pathogens. Instead, they work by attaching to them and signaling other parts of the immune system to destroy them.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They directly kill bacteria by puncturing their cell walls"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! These Y-shaped proteins (antibodies) attach to specific targets and essentially mark them for destruction. Other immune cells then recognize these markers and eliminate the tagged invaders.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "They tag the bacteria so other immune cells can find and destroy them"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Physical barriers like skin are separate from this targeting system. These proteins work by identifying and marking specific threats, not by blocking entry.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They form a physical barrier around wounds to prevent bacterial entry"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Engulfing pathogens is the job of cells like macrophages. These Y-shaped proteins work differently—they stick to invaders and flag them for destruction by other cells.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "They engulf and digest bacteria like cellular garbage collectors"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What is the function of these proteins?"
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "feedback": "The body's defenses work in layers. Physical barriers are always first. If breached, fast-acting cells respond immediately by consuming invaders. If the threat persists, the slower but more targeted response kicks in, producing specific antibodies. Finally, some cells retain information about the invader, preparing the body for faster responses if the same threat returns.",
      "items": [
        "Skin provides a barrier that bacteria must breach",
        "Cells that patrol tissues detect and consume invading bacteria",
        "Specialized cells produce proteins that target the specific bacteria",
        "Some immune cells store information about this bacteria for future encounters"
      ],
      "question": "Arrange what happens when bacteria enter through a scrape, from the first defense to the last response:"
    },
    {
      "format": "matchColumns",
      "pairs": [
        {
          "left": "Mucus in your nose traps dust and germs before they reach your lungs",
          "right": "Physical barrier defense"
        },
        {
          "left": "A cell engulfs a bacterium within minutes of it entering a wound",
          "right": "Rapid, non-specific response"
        },
        {
          "left": "Proteins that bind to one specific virus appear in the blood after a week of illness",
          "right": "Targeted antibody response"
        },
        {
          "left": "A person fights off a flu strain in 2 days instead of 2 weeks because they had it before",
          "right": "Memory-based immunity"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Match each immune scenario with the type of defense primarily responsible:"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "Two patients are infected with the same bacterial strain. Patient A has never encountered this bacteria before. Patient B had an infection with this exact bacteria two years ago. Both have healthy immune systems.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "A 'fresh' immune system doesn't respond faster. Previous exposure actually speeds up the targeted response because of cellular memory.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Patient A will produce antibodies faster because their immune system is fresh"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Patient B's immune system retains memory cells from the first infection. These cells recognize the bacteria immediately and trigger a rapid antibody response, clearing the infection much faster than Patient A's first-time response.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Patient B will clear the infection faster due to retained information about this bacteria"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Even with equally healthy immune systems, previous exposure makes a significant difference. The immune system learns from past infections.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Both patients will respond at the same speed since they have equally healthy immune systems"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Physical barriers work the same regardless of previous exposure. The difference lies in how quickly the targeted immune response activates.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Patient A's physical barriers will be more effective since they haven't been exposed before"
        }
      ],
      "question": "How will their responses likely differ?"
    },
    {
      "format": "fillBlank",
      "answers": [
        "quickly",
        "slower",
        "specific"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "randomly",
        "stronger",
        "weaker",
        "general",
        "permanent"
      ],
      "feedback": "The key trade-off in immune defense is speed versus specificity. The first defense system acts immediately but treats all invaders the same way. The second system takes longer to activate but produces highly targeted responses—antibodies that match specific invaders perfectly. This slower system also creates lasting memory.",
      "question": "Complete this description of how the two main defense systems differ:",
      "template": "The first line of defense responds [BLANK] but attacks all invaders the same way. The second line of defense is [BLANK] but creates responses tailored to [BLANK] threats."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "questions": [
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "int total = \"hello\";",
        "kind": "code"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Lexical analysis only breaks code into tokens. It would see 'int', 'total', '=', '\"hello\"', and ';' as valid tokens without understanding their relationships or types.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Lexical analysis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The parser checks syntax structure. This code has valid syntax - a type, variable name, assignment, value, and semicolon. The parser doesn't verify if the types are compatible.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Parsing"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! Semantic analysis checks if code makes logical sense. Assigning a string to an integer variable is syntactically valid but semantically wrong - the types don't match.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Semantic analysis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Code generation only happens after semantic analysis passes. This error would be caught before reaching that stage.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Code generation"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which compiler phase catches this error?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "if (x > 5 {\n    print(x)\n}",
        "kind": "code"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Each individual piece here - 'if', '(', 'x', '>', '5', '{', etc. - is a valid token. Lexical analysis doesn't check how tokens fit together.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Lexical analysis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The parser builds a tree structure and expects tokens to follow grammar rules. A missing closing parenthesis before the brace breaks the expected structure, so parsing fails.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Parsing"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Semantic analysis checks logical meaning, but this code never gets that far - it fails structurally before meaning can be evaluated.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Semantic analysis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Code generation is the final stage. Structural errors like this are caught much earlier in the process.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Code generation"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which compiler phase catches this error?"
    },
    {
      "format": "sortOrder",
      "feedback": "Each phase depends on the previous one's output. You can't build a structure until you have tokens. You can't check if types make sense until you understand the structure. And you can't generate working machine code until you've verified the program is logically valid.",
      "items": [
        "Break code into individual tokens",
        "Build a tree structure from tokens",
        "Verify logical correctness and type compatibility",
        "Generate machine instructions"
      ],
      "question": "A compiler processes source code through several stages. Arrange these phases in the order they must occur:"
    },
    {
      "format": "matchColumns",
      "pairs": [
        {
          "left": "Unexpected character '@#$' in source",
          "right": "Lexical analysis"
        },
        {
          "left": "Expected '}' but found end of file",
          "right": "Parsing"
        },
        {
          "left": "Cannot compare string with boolean",
          "right": "Semantic analysis"
        },
        {
          "left": "Unknown symbol 'func' near line 10",
          "right": "Lexical analysis"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Match each error message to the compiler phase that would catch it:"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "You're writing a simple calculator that evaluates expressions like '3 + 5 * 2'. Your program first splits the input into pieces: '3', '+', '5', '*', '2'. Then it figures out that multiplication should happen before addition based on operator precedence.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly! Splitting into pieces (tokens) is lexical analysis. Figuring out precedence and how operations relate is parsing - building structure from the tokens.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Lexical analysis followed by parsing"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Splitting into pieces isn't parsing - that's the tokenization step that comes first. Parsing uses those pieces to build structure.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Parsing followed by semantic analysis"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Neither step described here involves checking logical meaning (semantic) or producing machine code (generation). These are earlier structural steps.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Semantic analysis followed by code generation"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The calculator isn't generating machine code or executing yet - it's still figuring out the structure of the expression.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Code generation followed by execution"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Which compiler phases does this mirror?"
    },
    {
      "format": "fillBlank",
      "answers": [
        "tokens",
        "tree structure",
        "machine instructions"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "bytes",
        "binary code",
        "functions",
        "memory addresses",
        "symbol table"
      ],
      "feedback": "Compilers break code into tokens (smallest meaningful pieces), organize them into a tree structure (showing relationships like which operations belong to which statements), and ultimately produce machine instructions the CPU understands.",
      "question": "Complete this description of how a compiler transforms source code:",
      "template": "First, the source code is broken into [BLANK] - the smallest meaningful units like keywords and operators. These are then organized into a [BLANK] that shows how statements relate to each other. After verifying the code is logically valid, the compiler produces [BLANK] that the processor can execute."
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A developer notices their code editor highlighting 'whlie' in red as soon as they type it. The editor knows it's not a valid keyword, even before they finish the line or try to compile.",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Correct! The editor is doing real-time lexical analysis. It knows 'whlie' doesn't match any valid keyword, identifier pattern, or other token type in the language.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Lexical analysis recognizing an invalid token"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Parsing deals with how valid tokens fit together. Here, the problem is that 'whlie' itself isn't recognized as any valid token type.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Parsing detecting a structural error"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Semantic analysis checks logical meaning. This error is caught at the earliest stage - recognizing individual pieces of code.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Semantic analysis catching a type error"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Code generation happens at the very end. This error is caught immediately at the first stage of analysis.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Code generation failing to translate"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What type of analysis enables this?"
    },
    {
      "format": "multipleChoice",
      "context": {
        "description": "A student asks: 'Why can't compilers just read my code and produce machine instructions in one step? Why all these separate phases?'",
        "kind": "text"
      },
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly! Breaking compilation into phases lets each stage focus on one concern. Missing parentheses (structure), type mismatches (meaning), and unknown symbols (tokens) are different problems caught at different stages with specific error messages.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Each phase handles a different type of problem, making errors easier to identify and report"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "While historical limitations existed, the multi-phase approach persists because it's fundamentally better organized, not just a workaround for old hardware.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Older computers were too slow to do it in one step"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "There's no requirement for a specific number of phases. The phases exist because different kinds of analysis naturally separate - you need tokens before structure, structure before meaning.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Programming languages require exactly five phases by definition"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "This reverses the issue. The phases exist to progressively transform complex source code, breaking down the problem into manageable steps.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Machine code is too simple to understand high-level code directly"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What's the best explanation?"
    }
  ]
}

